{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632992"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:47:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:47:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17456"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70867"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10146"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56334"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70867"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWorkplace health and safety regulations specify maximum allowable noise exposure levels to prevent hearing damage. The reference exposure level is 85 decibels over an 8-hour work day.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between noise intensity and safe exposure duration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Safe exposure time doubles with each 5 decibel increase","Safe exposure time doubles with each 3 decibel increase","Safe exposure time halves with each 5 decibel increase","Safe exposure time remains constant regardless of decibel level","Safe exposure time halves with each 3 decibel increase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe relationship between noise intensity and safe exposure duration follows what is known as the 3 dB exchange rate. \u003Cstrong\u003ESafe exposure time halves with each 3 decibel increase\u003C/strong\u003E in noise level. For example, at 85 dB the safe exposure time is 8 hours, at 88 dB it is 4 hours, and at 91 dB it is 2 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESafe exposure time doubles with each 5 decibel increase\u003C/strong\u003E combines two incorrect concepts as the exchange rate is 3 dB and the relationship is inverse rather than direct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESafe exposure time doubles with each 3 decibel increase\u003C/strong\u003E suggests an incorrect direct relationship when the relationship is actually inverse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESafe exposure time halves with each 5 decibel increase\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; while this correctly identifies the inverse relationship, it uses an incorrect exchange rate of 5 dB instead of 3 dB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESafe exposure time remains constant regardless of decibel level\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate protection as higher noise levels require shorter exposure times to prevent hearing damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this relationship is crucial for implementing appropriate hearing protection measures in occupational settings. When noise levels exceed these limits, hearing protection devices must be used to reduce exposure to safe levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Occupational noise exposure above 85 decibels requires hearing protection to prevent noise-induced hearing loss.","Every 3 decibel increase in noise level halves the safe exposure time.","Hearing protection devices must reduce noise exposure to below 85 decibels over an 8-hour work day."],"references":["Deafness and hearing loss. World Health Organisation. Available from: https://www.who.int/news-room/questions-and-answers/item/deafness-and-hearing-loss-safe-listening"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56334"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17456"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56334"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:50:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:51:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10146"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70867"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group